  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and evolved gradually over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts emerged in the 1920s during Prohibition era United States\n- Targeting organized crime's financial transactions, particularly related to illegal alcohol trade\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970):\n- First comprehensive U.S. legislation requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established mandatory reporting and record-keeping requirements\n- Aimed at combating tax evasion and organized crime\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global financial crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989 to develop standardized AML strategies\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- U.S. Bank Secrecy Act amendments (1992)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Expanded scope to include terrorism financing prevention\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- Increasing international cooperation\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Enhanced cross-border financial monitoring\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
